AI at CES
---------

From the Las Vegas Sun ( https://lasvegassun.com/news/2024/jan/09/once-agai=
n-ces-will-transform-las-vegas-into-the-e/ ) :

Hundreds of thousands of people will descend on Las Vegas this week for CES=
, the annual electronics show bringing together industry leaders, governmen=
t officials, celebrities and a slew of exhibitors to show off what=E2=80=99=
s new in the world of technology. Running today through Friday, the show wh=
ich boasts more than 2.5 million square feet of exhibit space, is expected =
to bring more than 130,000 people to town, said Melissa Harrison, vice pres=
ident of marketing and communications at the Consumer Technology Associatio=
n, which owns and produces the annual event. =E2=80=9CThis is where busines=
s gets done,=E2=80=9D Harrison said. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re going to see t=
he greatest minds, the most powerful brands and most impactful technology.=
=E2=80=9D

I used to write about CES every year, but my last mention of the famous con=
sumer electronics show was in 2020, where I admitted that the event everyon=
e claims to hate but secretly loves had gotten pretty boring:

Bohn chalks the prevalence of foldable screen concepts, and lack of product=
s, up to a lack of confidence, both in foldable technology itself, and also=
 in what use cases it might have; John Gruber argues ( https://daringfireba=
ll.net/2020/01/concept_electronics_show ) that companies at CES don=E2=80=
=99t know how to design products.

Or, perhaps, there isn=E2=80=99t an obvious place for these companies to go=
. Again, I already cited the risk of confirmation bias, but once you have a=
 screen with you everywhere, slightly different screens, or, in the case of=
 wearables or voice control, no screens, is at best evolutionary, and likel=
y augmentative. Sure, something may materialize out of thin air, but even b=
ack in the 80s and 90s it was clear that both the Internet and mobile were =
going to be something big, if we could figure out how to get there. The fig=
uring out how to get there still exists, but what is the there?

The answer four years later is painfully obvious: AI! From Bloomberg ( http=
s://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2024-01-08/ai-pc-and-other-ai-gadget=
s-to-take-over-ces-2024-in-las-vegas ) :

Even before CES began, the theme of the massive, annual electronics festiva=
l in Las Vegas had long been decided: artificial intelligence gadgets. With=
 so much hype and money swirling around ChatGPT and its counterparts, it wa=
s inevitable that practically every device maker would jump on the AI bandw=
agon.

As much as CES serves as a hub for the products of tomorrow, it also typica=
lly doubles as a preview of how tech giants and startups will market their =
wares in the coming year. And if early announcements are any indication, AI=
-branded products will become the new =E2=80=9Csmart=E2=80=9D gadgets of 20=
24.

In the lead up to the event, LG Electronics Inc. touted AI television sets.=
 Samsung Electronics Co. will show off a vacuum bot that uses AI to detect =
stains and distinguish between hard floors and carpets. (The company is exp=
ected to separately launch an AI phone later this month). One startup is se=
t to debut an AI system for accelerating the ordering process at drive-thru=
 restaurants. Intel Corp. is simply promising to talk about =E2=80=9CAI eve=
rywhere.=E2=80=9D

The reality, of course, is that these are not simply the new =E2=80=9Csmart=
=E2=80=9D gadgets: they would probably be called =E2=80=9Csmart=E2=80=9D ga=
dgets absent the ChatGPT phenomenon: the =E2=80=9CAI=E2=80=9D is just thing=
s like vision recognition and a machine learning-derived algorithm to deter=
mine floor type; there are no large language models in a vacuum cleaner. To=
 put it another way, perhaps the biggest impact of ChatGPT on CES was that =
it stopped the goalpost-moving in terms of the word =E2=80=9CAI=E2=80=9D: f=
or years and years AI was the future, machine learning was the present, and=
 mere algorithms were the past, irrespective of the actual capabilities bei=
ng described. Now, though, AI is here =E2=80=94 in fact, it=E2=80=99s every=
where, no matter the underlying technology.

The Rabbit R1
-------------

That noted, the eye-catching gadget of the day was very much about AI, in t=
he ChatGPT vein. From TechCrunch ( https://techcrunch.com/2024/01/09/can-a-=
striking-design-set-rabbits-r1-pocket-ai-apart-from-a-gaggle-of-virtual-ass=
istants/ ) :

In a sea of AI-enabled gadgets at CES, the rabbit r1 (all lowercase, they i=
nsist) stands out not just for its high-vis paint job and unique form facto=
r, but because of its dedication to the bit. The company is hoping you=E2=
=80=99ll carry a second device around to save yourself the trouble of openi=
ng your phone =E2=80=94 and has gone to extraordinary technical lengths to =
make it work.

The idea behind the $200 r1 is simple: It lets you keep your phone in your =
pocket when you need to do some simple task like ordering a car to your loc=
ation, looking up a few places to eat where you=E2=80=99re meeting friends =
or finding some lodging options for a weekend on the coast.

=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re not trying to kill your phone,=E2=80=9D said CEO and=
 founder Jesse Lyu on a call with press ahead of the Las Vegas tech show. =
=E2=80=9CThe phone is an entertainment device, but if you=E2=80=99re trying=
 to get something done it=E2=80=99s not the highest efficiency machine. To =
arrange dinner with a colleague we needed four-five different apps to work =
together. Large language models are a universal solution for natural langua=
ge, we want a universal solution for these services =E2=80=94 they should j=
ust be able to understand you.=E2=80=9D

Instead of pulling out your phone, unlocking it, finding the app, opening i=
t and working your way through the UI (so laborious!), you pull out the r1 =
instead and give it a command in natural language=E2=80=A6The r1 does as yo=
u bid it and a few seconds later provides confirmation and any content you =
might have requested.

First off, the necessary caveat for the haters in the audience: yes, this d=
evice will almost certainly fail. Indeed, the business model =E2=80=94 a $2=
00 device with no subscription fee, despite the fact all of the actual comp=
uting happens in the cloud =E2=80=94 feels designed to fail. It=E2=80=99s a=
 pretty big red flag, particularly for a device that will depend on your gi=
ving user data to their cloud.

Moreover, the keynote ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D22wlLy7hKP4&t=3D3=
s ) =E2=80=94 which was clearly trying to ape an Apple keynote, both in vis=
ual appearance and also structure (show the problem, present a solution, do=
 some demos) =E2=80=94 was playing an awful lot of tricks in terms of what =
it actually showed on camera. Lyu would make audacious requests like asking=
 Rabbit to book flights and hotels and pronounce the task completed without=
 actually showing that it was completed. Then there is the fact that pre-or=
ders charge your credit card immediately without any assurance as to when y=
our order will ship (Lyu said Easter 2024, but there is no confirmation dat=
e on your order).

All that noted, I still found the product very interesting, starting with i=
ts appearance:

( https://www.rabbit.tech/ )

The Rabbit R1 was made in collaboration with Teenage Engineering, and looks=
 a lot like a Playdate ( https://play.date/ ). More importantly, it looks f=
un , in a way other AI hardware like the Humane AI Pin ( https://hu.ma.ne/ =
) do not. The biggest difference, though, is the intentionality of the desi=
gn: you interact with the Rabbit R1 by pressing the button on the side like=
 a walkie-talkie, and the AI responds to you both verbally and on the LCD s=
creen, which is touch-sensitive. It seems both more natural and foolproof t=
han speaking to an ambient device like a pin or pendant or even glasses, ev=
en if there is obvious friction in pulling it out of your pocket.

I do, given the current state of AI, see friction as a positive in this cas=
e, but that mention is a bit of a problem for the Rabbit R1 value propositi=
on, which is about removing it: the problem Lyu claims Rabbit is solving is=
 the trouble of navigating multiple apps on your phone to get a job done, i=
nstead of just saying what you want. And, needless to say, this is another =
reason the product will fail: it=E2=80=99s really not that hard to call an =
Uber on your phone.

The part that is interesting to me, though, is the promised speed of intera=
ction with AI. It was speed =E2=80=94 or rather the lack of it =E2=80=94 an=
d friction =E2=80=94 the abundance of it =E2=80=94 that frustrated me when =
using ChatGPT=E2=80=99s voice mode. From AI, Hardware, and Virtual Reality =
( https://stratechery.com/2023/ai-hardware-and-virtual-reality/?access_toke=
n=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR=
5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS=
0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5=
LmNvbS8yMDIzL2FpLWhhcmR3YXJlLWFuZC12aXJ0dWFsLXJlYWxpdHkvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MDc=
0ODY4NDEsImlhdCI6MTcwNDg5NDg0MSwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW=
5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0Z=
Wdvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwi=
dXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.TcdajCPdA3FnGzPs0yrRwmKoeZ98vFymOxdR9pC9WzBxvk2sPVX8f-R=
lvUL5Al5l0IkrI2t-Eu2NKvSMiYLGNNmo4_I0IvFze7lM_STWfn2rzY8OebW3_b03S6knBPNVT_=
RbCa5TPXr8g-Qp7_KUDc8O-xjfkotGqfjsz3-cfSP3nukoHYddTg8VWXv9DF2mmOTCo_Kco72ab=
bj00M6XkgFDNvlHOXiqtEl4SXvWDXBAJtqI1Kl--GiI3kfKjdKLMy2nfyZHTo-VPAQJ6rYy0omb=
CMbi8lxQjxWj46Wykt0XVs3SeGGEYbACZun0oHyDfM2-pm3jWs3i1RffFWlxqg ) :

AI is truly something new and revolutionary and capable of being something =
more than just a homework aid, but I don=E2=80=99t think the existing inter=
faces are the right ones. Talking to ChatGPT is better than typing, but I s=
till have to launch the app and set the mode; vision is an amazing capabili=
ty, but it requires even more intent and friction to invoke.

What the Rabbit R1 seeks to do is lower the invocation costs, and I think t=
hat is a worthy goal.

The device, though, is only part of the value proposition: I mentioned that=
 all of the actual compute is happening on the cloud, in this case via agen=
ts. The idea is that Rabbit has created what they call a =E2=80=9CLarge Act=
ion Model=E2=80=9D which is trained on graphical user interfaces to underst=
and their different components, what buttons do, how content is organized o=
n a website, etc. What that means is that when a user makes a request =E2=
=80=94 =E2=80=9CPlay Taylor Swift=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 the cloud application =
actually navigates the Spotify interface (assuming you have logged in via O=
Auth on your =E2=80=9CRabbit Hole=E2=80=9D website) and plays Taylor Swift.

Agent capability and sustainability are, needless to say, an open question,=
 particularly in these early days. What is so enticing about the approach, =
though, is that it provides the promise of massive compatibility without ha=
ving to actual recruit developers to your platform. Indeed, this might be t=
he business case for the hardware: it=E2=80=99s the most interesting and ey=
e-catching way for Rabbit to show off their =E2=80=9Clarge action model=E2=
=80=9D.

This part of the experience could, of course, be done in an app. Again, tho=
ugh, why bother going to the Rabbit app when you can just go to Spotify dir=
ectly? In this I think that the hardware device, even if it is just ultimat=
ely a demo you can pay for, matters: for an agent approach to be better it =
has to be seamless, and given the locked-down state of phones it is impossi=
ble to build a seamless experience without hardware. To that end, while Rab=
bit may not end up winning in this space, I do think it is a step in a prom=
ising direction, and I applaud the effort (and yes, I=E2=80=99m ready for a=
 Siri that does all of this on device; maybe Lyu was pitching Tim Cook dire=
ctly).

